WEBVTT

00:04.047 --> 00:04.265
.

00:04.308 --> 00:06.702
[upbeat music]

00:06.745 --> 00:09.270
- 31,252.

00:09.313 --> 00:11.011
- Is that how many times
the Dean called?

00:11.054 --> 00:12.577
- According to my Fitbit,
that's how many steps

00:12.621 --> 00:14.405
it's taken to keep up with you.

00:14.449 --> 00:16.625
Here.
- I don't want another apple.

00:16.668 --> 00:18.583
- Also Dean of Medicine
needs you.

00:18.627 --> 00:19.628
- Tell him I'm
eating an apple.

00:19.671 --> 00:20.672
- You can tell him yourself.

00:20.716 --> 00:21.760
- I need to sustain my energy.

00:21.804 --> 00:23.284
- He's in your office.

00:23.327 --> 00:28.811
♪

00:28.854 --> 00:29.812
- Dean.

00:29.855 --> 00:31.422
♪

00:31.466 --> 00:34.251
- You're fired.

00:34.295 --> 00:35.687
- [sighs]

00:35.731 --> 00:39.648
[horns honking,
sirens blaring]

00:39.691 --> 00:41.258
- You're fired.

00:41.302 --> 00:42.651
- Okay.

00:42.694 --> 00:45.306
- I said you're fired.

00:45.349 --> 00:47.612
- And I said okay.

00:49.223 --> 00:50.702
- What do you mean, okay?

00:50.746 --> 00:52.704
Two months ago you were
practically begging me

00:52.748 --> 00:53.836
for this job.

00:53.879 --> 00:55.446
- A lot's changed
in two months.

00:55.490 --> 00:57.579
Two months ago this country
had health insurance.

00:57.622 --> 00:59.755
Two months ago I was still
living with my wife.

00:59.798 --> 01:01.452
- Please don't tell me
that you're having

01:01.496 --> 01:02.584
a nervous breakdown,
because that's what this

01:02.627 --> 01:04.238
sounds like to me.

01:04.281 --> 01:06.240
- Nope, this is just me trying
to help this hospital.

01:06.283 --> 01:08.068
- How can you say that
when you've eliminated

01:08.111 --> 01:10.766
the cardiac surgery program,
you have gutted the highest

01:10.809 --> 01:12.507
source of revenue that
this hospital produces--

01:12.550 --> 01:14.117
- Either I shut it down

01:14.161 --> 01:15.379
or the New York Department
of Health would have.

01:15.423 --> 01:17.816
- Max, you hired
50 new attendings.

01:17.860 --> 01:19.601
50!

01:19.644 --> 01:22.430
You cut the balls off my
residents--my training program.

01:22.473 --> 01:24.388
- Some of those residents
have ovaries.

01:24.432 --> 01:25.520
And when people come
to this hospital,

01:25.563 --> 01:27.217
you know what they never say?

01:27.261 --> 01:29.393
"I'm sick and dying, so
let me train your residents."

01:29.437 --> 01:31.569
- This is a job
of a lifetime, son.

01:31.613 --> 01:32.875
This is the big leagues.

01:32.918 --> 01:34.311
And you're just
throwing it away.

01:34.355 --> 01:35.573
- You hired me to make changes.

01:35.617 --> 01:36.618
- That's right.
My changes.

01:36.661 --> 01:38.185
- Your changes aren't working.

01:38.228 --> 01:39.490
They haven't worked
for 20 years.

01:39.534 --> 01:41.101
And you know that.

01:41.144 --> 01:42.841
You must, otherwise you
wouldn't have hired me.

01:42.885 --> 01:45.322
But you chose me

01:45.366 --> 01:47.542
because deep down,
you care about this place

01:47.585 --> 01:49.239
as much as I do.

01:51.459 --> 01:53.722
- When I hired you, I thought
that you would be grateful.

01:53.765 --> 01:55.158
- I am grateful.

01:55.202 --> 01:57.334
- I thought that you
would be compliant.

01:57.378 --> 01:58.814
- I'm not compliant.

01:58.857 --> 02:00.337
- Yeah, that's for sure.

02:00.381 --> 02:02.339
Well, I'm not gonna
make that mistake again.

02:02.383 --> 02:04.733
And why are you wearing scrubs?

02:04.776 --> 02:06.300
- Because I'm a doctor.

02:07.736 --> 02:10.173
If you fire me,
you will help save my marriage

02:10.217 --> 02:12.175
and I will be
eternally grateful.

02:12.219 --> 02:14.612
If you let me stay,
I will do everything I can

02:14.656 --> 02:17.876
to save this hospital, and
you will get all the credit.

02:19.878 --> 02:21.837
- You have six months.
- Give me three.

02:21.880 --> 02:24.840
[percussive music]

02:24.883 --> 02:31.673
♪

02:31.716 --> 02:35.894
- Maddy, I'm sorry.
I need to see you.

02:35.938 --> 02:39.159
I'm sorry.
I'm so sorry.

02:39.202 --> 02:41.596
I'm so sorry.

02:41.639 --> 02:43.337
Maddy,
I need you back.

02:43.380 --> 02:45.904
I need to be with you.

02:45.948 --> 02:52.172
[sirens blaring]

02:57.307 --> 02:58.265
- What time's the prisoner
coming in?

02:58.308 --> 03:01.616
- Any minute.

03:01.659 --> 03:03.792
Guys, we got a patient
from Rikers coming in.

03:03.835 --> 03:05.576
So let's clear this area.

03:05.620 --> 03:08.840
[doors opening and closing]

03:08.884 --> 03:13.541
♪

03:13.584 --> 03:15.934
And let's lose any equipment
that might be weaponized.

03:15.978 --> 03:17.675
- Is a toothbrush weaponizable?

03:17.719 --> 03:20.809
- Yeah, yeah, especially
in the war on tarter.

03:20.852 --> 03:23.681
That's not the prisoner.

03:23.725 --> 03:26.336
- Cops found him in a cemetery
digging up a grave.

03:26.380 --> 03:28.643
His vitals are normal,
but nothing else is.

03:28.686 --> 03:29.905
- Hey, what's your name, sir?

03:29.948 --> 03:31.254
- Ray.

03:31.298 --> 03:32.864
- Hey, Ray.
I'm Dr. Bloom.

03:32.908 --> 03:34.953
Would you mind just,
uh, looking at me?

03:34.997 --> 03:36.955
- I'm wasn't doing
anything wrong.

03:36.999 --> 03:38.696
[dramatic music]

03:38.740 --> 03:41.612
I've lost her.

03:41.656 --> 03:42.831
- Who?

03:42.874 --> 03:44.746
- Maddy.

03:44.789 --> 03:47.879
My fiancée.

03:47.923 --> 03:50.882
She's gone.

03:50.926 --> 03:52.406
Everything's gone.

03:52.449 --> 03:54.625
♪

03:54.669 --> 03:56.236
- Let's, uh...

03:56.279 --> 03:57.759
Let's clean him up
and run a tox screen.

03:57.802 --> 03:59.369
And get psych down here.

03:59.413 --> 04:04.026
Let's clear that bay
for the prisoner.

04:04.069 --> 04:09.249
[sirens blaring]

04:09.292 --> 04:16.299
♪

04:21.609 --> 04:22.958
- Dr. Bloom?

04:23.001 --> 04:24.568
- That's me.

04:24.612 --> 04:28.398
- Where do you want her?

04:31.967 --> 04:34.926
[dramatic music]

04:34.970 --> 04:40.410
♪

04:40.454 --> 04:41.803
- [sighs]

04:41.846 --> 04:44.588
♪

04:44.632 --> 04:47.287
[toilet flushes]

04:47.330 --> 04:50.290
[sink running]

04:50.333 --> 04:57.340
♪

04:58.036 --> 05:01.301
[door opens and closes]

05:04.565 --> 05:07.568
- Max?
I need you to sign these.

05:07.611 --> 05:08.830
- Wow, am I being sued?

05:08.873 --> 05:09.961
- Every time you
change a rule,

05:10.005 --> 05:11.311
you need to sign.

05:11.354 --> 05:12.486
- Remind me to
change that rule.

05:12.529 --> 05:13.791
- Oh, wait,
where are you going?

05:13.835 --> 05:15.097
The staff meeting's that way.

05:15.140 --> 05:16.533
- Right, but my wife
is this way.

05:16.577 --> 05:17.839
- Max.
- Dr. Sharpe.

05:17.882 --> 05:18.927
Max, we need to talk
about your treatment.

05:18.970 --> 05:20.581
- Not here, we don't.

05:20.624 --> 05:21.756
- How long do you think you
can keep this a secret?

05:21.799 --> 05:22.844
- Public hallway, Sharpe.

05:22.887 --> 05:24.062
- Before you even start chemo,

05:24.106 --> 05:25.716
we have to take
out your molars,

05:25.760 --> 05:27.718
PEG insertion,
IV ports all over your body--

05:27.762 --> 05:28.763
- I know the drill.

05:28.806 --> 05:30.025
- But you're the patient now.

05:30.068 --> 05:32.419
- Exactly.
"Physician heal thyself."

05:32.462 --> 05:34.464
- You do realize that phrase
is about a physician

05:34.508 --> 05:36.640
who helps others
but not himself, right?

05:36.684 --> 05:38.338
- All right, bad example.

05:38.381 --> 05:39.774
But I don't need you to be
my doctor because, you know,

05:39.817 --> 05:41.471
I am a doctor.

05:41.515 --> 05:42.951
I just need you to bounce
ideas off of, like a guide.

05:42.994 --> 05:44.866
Or a Sherpa.
- A Sherpa?

05:44.909 --> 05:46.737
- Yeah.
All right, another bad example.

05:46.781 --> 05:47.912
But just come on.
Roll with me here.

05:47.956 --> 05:48.913
- Have you told your wife?

05:48.957 --> 05:50.741
- Uh, no.

05:50.785 --> 05:52.395
- Max.
- I couldn't.

05:52.439 --> 05:53.657
She's on bed rest.

05:53.701 --> 05:54.963
But as soon as she
feels better,

05:55.006 --> 05:55.964
I will tell her.
- Hey, Max.

05:56.007 --> 05:57.531
- Dr. Reynolds.

05:57.574 --> 05:58.619
How's the, uh,
department search coming?

05:58.662 --> 06:00.011
- Excellent.

06:00.055 --> 06:01.404
We got three new attendings
coming in today.

06:01.448 --> 06:02.840
Thank you.
- All great hires.

06:02.884 --> 06:04.494
- Hey, this is going
to be the most innovative

06:04.538 --> 06:05.582
cardiac surgery department
in the country.

06:05.626 --> 06:07.149
- That's what I wanna hear.

06:07.192 --> 06:08.890
- And just for the record,
I don't agree with this plan,

06:08.933 --> 06:10.021
if you can even call it that.

06:10.065 --> 06:11.632
- Noted.
Food for thought.

06:11.675 --> 06:13.721
See, this dynamic
is working already.

06:21.772 --> 06:23.861
- Morning.
- Perfect timing.

06:23.905 --> 06:24.993
- Really?
What do you need?

06:25.036 --> 06:26.473
Breakfast?
Water?

06:26.516 --> 06:27.952
- My clothes.

06:27.996 --> 06:29.693
They're releasing me today.

06:29.737 --> 06:30.999
- What?

06:31.042 --> 06:32.870
- That's good news, Max.

06:32.914 --> 06:35.438
- Yeah--Uh, yeah.
Yeah.

06:35.482 --> 06:36.744
That's good.

06:36.787 --> 06:40.922
That's good, it's just so soon.

06:40.965 --> 06:45.187
- Well, Suzanne says I'm ready.

06:45.230 --> 06:49.452
- Well, you can't go back
to the apartment alone.

06:49.496 --> 06:51.933
- I'm not.

06:51.976 --> 06:54.718
I'm gonna go stay
at my folks' place.

06:54.762 --> 06:57.939
- In Connecticut?

06:57.982 --> 07:00.071
I'm never gonna see you.

07:00.115 --> 07:02.726
- My mom is there.

07:02.770 --> 07:04.162
And I need the help.

07:04.206 --> 07:08.906
[dramatic music]

07:08.950 --> 07:10.081
What?

07:10.125 --> 07:12.519
What, you want me to stay here?

07:12.562 --> 07:14.782
- Yeah.

07:14.825 --> 07:16.218
- [laughs]

07:16.261 --> 07:18.568
Max, you are the only
person in the world

07:18.612 --> 07:20.570
who actually likes hospitals.

07:20.614 --> 07:23.051
[knocking]

07:23.094 --> 07:24.618
- Sorry to intrude.

07:24.661 --> 07:26.010
- I know I'm late
for the staff meeting.

07:26.054 --> 07:30.014
- Actually, the Dean
just started without you.

07:30.058 --> 07:31.929
- Arthur Ryland
was a great friend.

07:31.973 --> 07:33.627
He was a wonderful friend.

07:33.670 --> 07:35.933
And not just to me,
but to this institution.

07:35.977 --> 07:39.763
And I'm happy to report that
in his will he pledged

07:39.807 --> 07:42.897
$10 million to our
network of hospitals.

07:42.940 --> 07:47.597
But per his widow,
only one will get the money.

07:47.641 --> 07:50.513
I game Mrs. Ryland a tour
of University yesterday,

07:50.557 --> 07:52.820
and she was very impressed,
but she still wants

07:52.863 --> 07:55.518
to visit New Amsterdam.

07:55.562 --> 07:58.129
As a teaching hospital,
I suspect she wants to see

07:58.173 --> 07:59.914
how you make the sausage.

07:59.957 --> 08:01.481
- Sausage?

08:04.658 --> 08:06.964
- It's a figure of speech, Max.

08:07.008 --> 08:08.749
She wants you
to take her around.

08:08.792 --> 08:11.665
So be charming.
Just not too charming.

08:11.708 --> 08:13.667
- Right, because
you've earmarked

08:13.710 --> 08:15.669
her money for University?

08:15.712 --> 08:19.629
- Ah, I'm aware of your
budgetary needs,

08:19.673 --> 08:23.633
so if you go with me here,
the love will trickle down.

08:23.677 --> 08:26.636
That clear?
- Crystal.

08:26.680 --> 08:28.159
- Good.

08:31.119 --> 08:33.687
[percussive music]

08:33.730 --> 08:35.863
- So who wants $10 million?

08:40.389 --> 08:40.563
.

08:40.607 --> 08:46.395
[overlapping chatter]

08:46.438 --> 08:50.486
- Uh, you missed
an important call?

08:50.530 --> 08:54.751
- Oh, I was expecting one,
but I'm beginning to think

08:54.795 --> 08:57.275
it won't come.
- Oh, ghosted.

08:57.319 --> 08:58.668
That sucks.

08:58.712 --> 09:02.585
Is that why it's chocolate
croissant day?

09:02.629 --> 09:06.850
The furrowed brow pick-me-up?
[laughs]

09:06.894 --> 09:10.375
- I was not aware
that I furrowed.

09:10.419 --> 09:12.377
- Well, we're always
the last to know.

09:12.421 --> 09:13.465
[laughs]

09:13.509 --> 09:15.598
- Are you new here?

09:15.642 --> 09:17.731
- Two weeks.
But I notice things.

09:17.774 --> 09:22.126
♪

09:22.170 --> 09:23.432
- Thank you.
- Mm-hmm.

09:23.475 --> 09:26.217
Bye.

09:27.784 --> 09:29.351
- [grunts]
Okay.

09:29.394 --> 09:32.615
Janelle, your blood pressure
is way too high.

09:32.659 --> 09:33.834
You may be developing
a condition

09:33.877 --> 09:35.618
known as preeclampsia.

09:35.662 --> 09:37.533
We're gonna send out for some
more tests to confirm,

09:37.577 --> 09:39.622
but--
- What about my baby?

09:39.666 --> 09:42.451
- The baby's fine for now,
but we need to stay on this.

09:42.494 --> 09:45.541
Hang one bag normal saline
and start magnesium sulfate

09:45.585 --> 09:48.762
and a hydralazine drip titrated
to systolic under 140,

09:48.805 --> 09:50.633
and send for a U/A ASAP.

09:50.677 --> 09:52.243
- You got it, Dr. Bloom.

09:52.287 --> 09:54.115
- Ow.

09:54.158 --> 09:56.291
- Hey, uh, can we--can
we take those off her?

09:56.334 --> 09:57.597
- Not in a unsecure area.

09:57.640 --> 09:59.163
- Well, look,
the more she pulls,

09:59.207 --> 10:00.730
the higher her blood
pressure's gonna go.

10:00.774 --> 10:02.732
- They're for your safety
as well as hers, ma'am.

10:02.776 --> 10:03.777
- [scoffs]

10:03.820 --> 10:05.256
Okay, look.

10:05.300 --> 10:06.693
I don't really see
a threat here.

10:06.736 --> 10:07.781
I mean, what was her crime?

10:07.824 --> 10:10.305
- Felony robbery.

10:10.348 --> 10:12.873
- So, shoplifting?

10:12.916 --> 10:14.788
I'll take responsibility, okay?

10:14.831 --> 10:16.485
This is my ED.
She's my patient.

10:16.528 --> 10:18.313
- But she's my prisoner.

10:18.356 --> 10:21.316
[percussive music]

10:21.359 --> 10:24.841
♪

10:24.885 --> 10:26.669
- Ray DeMarco?

10:26.713 --> 10:29.193
I'm Dr. Iggy Frome.

10:29.237 --> 10:31.674
So, I hear you've been doing
a little grave digging.

10:33.720 --> 10:35.199
Naked.

10:36.548 --> 10:37.549
I'm not judging.

10:37.593 --> 10:39.682
Just, uh--
Just asking.

10:41.423 --> 10:43.381
- I didn't wanna
ruin new clothes.

10:44.861 --> 10:47.298
- Okay.
Got it.

10:47.342 --> 10:48.604
All right.
[clears throat]

10:48.648 --> 10:51.259
Why don't you tell
me about Maddy?

10:52.390 --> 10:53.914
- She was my fiancée.

10:57.657 --> 10:58.962
My best friend.

11:01.573 --> 11:04.707
Uh, we were gonna get
married in a month.

11:04.751 --> 11:07.536
[breathes deeply]

11:07.579 --> 11:10.495
So, um, to lose
her like this...

11:10.539 --> 11:12.846
- All right, I'm sorry.

11:12.889 --> 11:15.587
Your toxicology report
came back clean,

11:15.631 --> 11:18.416
but you've been putting
something in your body, right?

11:19.026 --> 11:22.203
The tracks on your arm?

11:22.246 --> 11:24.727
- What arm?

11:24.771 --> 11:27.730
[dramatic music]

11:27.774 --> 11:30.602
♪

11:30.646 --> 11:32.648
- You feel that?

11:32.692 --> 11:36.260
- No.

11:36.304 --> 11:39.394
- How about there?

11:39.437 --> 11:42.223
- Why would I feel anything?

11:42.266 --> 11:43.746
I'm invisible.

11:43.790 --> 11:49.752
♪

11:51.711 --> 11:53.364
- Mrs. Ryland.
Max Goodwin.

11:53.408 --> 11:54.365
- How do you do?

11:54.409 --> 11:55.758
- Thank you for coming.

11:55.802 --> 11:57.804
I'm so sorry to hear
about your husband.

11:57.847 --> 11:59.414
So, how much time do we have?

11:59.457 --> 12:00.763
- I've cleared the day.

12:00.807 --> 12:02.330
- Great, because I wanna
introduce you to all

12:02.373 --> 12:03.810
of our department heads.

12:03.853 --> 12:05.550
- When my husband had
his first heart attack,

12:05.594 --> 12:06.595
the people here saved him.

12:06.638 --> 12:08.423
- Here?

12:08.466 --> 12:10.512
- The Dean wants Arthur's money
to go elsewhere, of course.

12:10.555 --> 12:12.775
But the ultimate
decision is mine, so...

12:14.995 --> 12:17.911
Lead on and we'll see
where providence takes us.

12:17.954 --> 12:21.828
- We're better than
Providence, too.

12:21.871 --> 12:23.568
- Well, if you spent
any time here,

12:23.612 --> 12:25.788
you know that the Dam
is like a small city.

12:25.832 --> 12:27.790
We have our own school,
our own court room,

12:27.834 --> 12:28.791
a medical library.

12:28.835 --> 12:29.923
- And you're new, correct?

12:29.966 --> 12:31.576
- Well, yeah.
Five days.

12:31.620 --> 12:33.535
- So maybe I know more
about the place than you do.

12:33.578 --> 12:35.450
- Well, uh, maybe more
about where it's been.

12:35.493 --> 12:36.799
But I can tell you
where it's going.

12:36.843 --> 12:39.410
Dr. Sharpe.
This is Mrs. Ryland.

12:39.454 --> 12:41.935
This is Dr. Sharpe,
our head of oncology.

12:41.978 --> 12:44.372
- Pleasure.
- What a radiant smile.

12:44.415 --> 12:46.635
[laughs]
How do you keep it up?

12:46.678 --> 12:47.679
- Excuse me?

12:49.029 --> 12:50.900
- Billions of dollars spent
on cancer research

12:50.944 --> 12:53.642
and still no cure.

12:53.685 --> 12:57.298
- Oh, well, we've made
lots of strides.

12:57.341 --> 13:00.475
But you're right.
Cancer is relentless.

13:00.518 --> 13:01.868
And expensive.

13:01.911 --> 13:04.087
Especially in this new
era of cost control.

13:04.131 --> 13:06.524
We're constantly under water
caring for patients

13:06.568 --> 13:07.612
who can hardly afford it.

13:07.656 --> 13:09.789
- That's a Birkin, isn't it?

13:09.832 --> 13:12.052
$15,000.

13:12.095 --> 13:14.010
If you're having trouble
keeping your head above water,

13:14.054 --> 13:16.404
that bag ought
to help you float.

13:16.447 --> 13:18.710
- [laughs]
There's a lot to see.

13:18.754 --> 13:21.713
[percussive music]

13:21.757 --> 13:22.845
♪

13:22.889 --> 13:24.368
- My shift is up.
Who's coming on?

13:24.412 --> 13:25.848
- Candelario.

13:25.892 --> 13:27.502
- Okay, tell him we've got
a bleeder in bay two

13:27.545 --> 13:29.417
and we've got a hip fracture
awaiting ortho consult

13:29.460 --> 13:31.071
for an ORIF in three.

13:31.114 --> 13:32.986
- Dr. Bloom,
Janelle's urine came back.

13:33.029 --> 13:34.335
Protein's sky high
and her arm's bruised

13:34.378 --> 13:35.640
where we took
the blood pressure.

13:35.684 --> 13:36.685
- That's more than
preeclampsia.

13:36.728 --> 13:38.600
- Okay, test her for HELLPS.

13:38.643 --> 13:39.993
If we find it, then the baby's
gonna have to come out now.

13:40.036 --> 13:41.908
- HELLPS?
- Blood not clotting.

13:41.951 --> 13:44.562
[phones ringing]

13:44.606 --> 13:46.042
She's terrified.

13:46.086 --> 13:48.828
- Candelario can handle it.

13:48.871 --> 13:51.395
- Candelario can handle the ED.
I'll stick with Janelle.

13:51.439 --> 13:53.528
- You've been on for 12.
You're not allowed.

13:53.571 --> 13:55.965
- This is my own time.
And I need an OB.

13:56.009 --> 13:57.358
- On it.

13:57.401 --> 14:00.361
[percussive music]

14:00.404 --> 14:06.889
♪

14:06.933 --> 14:08.848
- You know, at first I thought
it was a schizophrenic break

14:08.891 --> 14:10.110
triggered by the death
of his fiancée.

14:10.153 --> 14:11.894
- Certainly possible.
- Excuse me.

14:11.938 --> 14:13.765
- Yeah, of course, but, uh,
now I'm super confused

14:13.809 --> 14:15.637
because he can't feel his arms.

14:15.680 --> 14:16.943
- Any drugs in his system?

14:16.986 --> 14:18.901
- He's got tracks,
but the tests came back

14:18.945 --> 14:22.470
completely clean.
No ketamine, to PCP, nothing.

14:22.513 --> 14:24.515
You know, there was a bit
of an odd anoin gap in there,

14:24.559 --> 14:25.734
so I ordered some more labs.

14:25.777 --> 14:26.735
- He needs an MRI.

14:26.778 --> 14:27.997
- Agreed, doctor.

14:28.041 --> 14:30.391
But, uh, that is not
the weirdest part.

14:30.434 --> 14:31.958
He thinks that he's invisible.

14:33.611 --> 14:34.656
That's why he can't
feel anything.

14:34.699 --> 14:35.787
There's nothing there to feel.

14:35.831 --> 14:39.530
- Invisible?
- Invisible.

14:43.056 --> 14:46.189
Ray?

14:46.233 --> 14:47.669
- Man might have a point.

14:53.240 --> 14:53.414
.

14:53.457 --> 14:55.459
He can't have gone too far.

14:55.503 --> 14:56.678
- If he's invisible,
how would we know?

14:56.721 --> 14:58.245
- Oh, get it out
of your system.

14:58.288 --> 14:59.246
You done?

14:59.289 --> 15:01.161
Hey, uh, Mason.

15:01.204 --> 15:02.336
Listen, we got a runner.

15:02.379 --> 15:04.120
Male, uh, average build,
mid-30s.

15:04.164 --> 15:05.556
- You want all exits covered?

15:05.600 --> 15:06.688
- And notification
the minute you see him.

15:06.731 --> 15:08.690
- Assuming that's possible.

15:08.733 --> 15:11.171
- Uh, would you stop?

15:11.214 --> 15:12.172
- What about Max's
$10 million woman?

15:12.215 --> 15:13.608
- What about her?

15:13.651 --> 15:14.826
- Do you really want her
to know there's an escaped

15:14.870 --> 15:16.567
psych patient on the loose?

15:16.611 --> 15:19.353
- Uh, yeah, Mason, hey, uh,
hold off on the PA, all right?

15:19.396 --> 15:21.355
Let's go walkies only.
Old school.

15:21.398 --> 15:23.052
All right?
Okay.

15:23.096 --> 15:25.185
- Thought we would swing
through pediatrics

15:25.228 --> 15:26.708
and then maybe stop by the ICU.

15:26.751 --> 15:28.666
Can I get you a water
or a coffee?

15:28.710 --> 15:30.668
- I'm fine.

15:30.712 --> 15:32.322
- Some of our
patients' artwork.

15:32.366 --> 15:33.715
- Kids?
- Mm-hmm.

15:33.758 --> 15:35.760
Our psych department
is second to none.

15:35.804 --> 15:38.763
Some very interesting people
have come through those...

15:38.807 --> 15:40.069
[percussive music]

15:40.113 --> 15:41.679
Doors.

15:41.723 --> 15:44.813
Huh, never know
what you're gonna see.

15:44.856 --> 15:45.814
[clears throat]

15:45.857 --> 15:50.514
♪

15:50.558 --> 15:52.212
- You mind if we record this?

15:52.255 --> 15:53.735
We're meeting with lots
of potential doctors,

15:53.778 --> 15:55.258
so we want to remember
everything.

15:55.302 --> 15:56.564
- Of course.

15:56.607 --> 15:58.174
- Dr. Helen doesn't
mind cameras.

15:58.218 --> 16:00.307
You're used to it from TV,
right?

16:00.350 --> 16:02.483
- So, Dr. Lalani
recommended you.

16:02.526 --> 16:03.658
- Yeah, she thinks
you're great.

16:03.701 --> 16:05.225
- Nasreen is a good friend.

16:05.268 --> 16:07.183
And one of the best
internists in the city.

16:07.227 --> 16:09.359
- We've both seen you
on television, of course.

16:09.403 --> 16:10.534
- You're great there, too.

16:10.578 --> 16:11.796
- But we were both wondering

16:11.840 --> 16:14.756
what your actual
qualifications are.

16:14.799 --> 16:16.410
- My qualifications?

16:16.453 --> 16:20.457
- To practice for real.

16:22.242 --> 16:24.809
- Well...
[laughs]

16:24.853 --> 16:27.160
Cambridge.

16:27.203 --> 16:29.423
Cambridge School
of Clinical Medicine.

16:29.466 --> 16:31.468
Foundation Doctor
and Specialty Registrar

16:31.512 --> 16:33.340
at Kings College
Hospital London.

16:33.383 --> 16:35.516
Additional residencies
and fellowships

16:35.559 --> 16:37.213
here at Columbia-Presbyterian,

16:37.257 --> 16:40.303
Board Certified in Adult
and Pediatric Hematology

16:40.347 --> 16:41.478
and Oncology.

16:41.522 --> 16:43.611
- Wow.
No wonder she's so busy.

16:43.654 --> 16:45.395
- Sorry?

16:45.439 --> 16:47.484
- We had a difficult time
getting an appointment.

16:47.528 --> 16:49.443
Almost three weeks.

16:50.879 --> 16:53.229
- I apologize.

16:53.273 --> 16:56.711
I've had, um, a number
of outside commitments.

16:56.754 --> 16:59.366
- Uh, Dr. Lalani said
your work was going

16:59.409 --> 17:01.629
to be more patient-focused now.

17:01.672 --> 17:04.153
- My patients have
always come first.

17:06.329 --> 17:08.375
But raising awareness
for New Amsterdam

17:08.418 --> 17:10.464
is a big part
of my job as well.

17:10.507 --> 17:11.813
- Hah.

17:14.163 --> 17:17.123
[dramatic music]

17:17.166 --> 17:18.820
♪

17:18.863 --> 17:23.651
- I'm gonna be cutting
back on press.

17:23.694 --> 17:26.219
- I'm sorry, Dr. Sharpe,
we're gonna need someone

17:26.262 --> 17:28.569
who will put Anna's
needs first.

17:28.612 --> 17:30.310
Not the camera.

17:30.353 --> 17:35.489
♪

17:35.532 --> 17:37.882
- And how did your
husband end up here?

17:37.926 --> 17:39.928
- He was on his way
to a meeting downtown

17:39.971 --> 17:41.190
and had chest pains.

17:41.234 --> 17:42.365
The driver brought him in.

17:42.409 --> 17:43.975
- And any issues after?

17:44.019 --> 17:45.629
- Besides having
another heart attack?

17:45.673 --> 17:46.761
[laughs]

17:46.804 --> 17:48.415
It wasn't the hospital's fault.

17:48.458 --> 17:51.157
Arthur's mistresses
were steaks and cigars.

17:51.200 --> 17:53.246
- Ah.
- And money, of course.

17:53.289 --> 17:55.291
- Dr. Reynolds.
I'd like you to meet someone.

17:55.335 --> 17:56.858
- Mrs. Ryland, I presume.

17:56.901 --> 17:59.730
- Dr. Reynolds is our new Chair
of Cardiothoracic Surgery.

17:59.774 --> 18:01.863
- Ah, and you ladies are?

18:01.906 --> 18:04.518
- Dr. Hastings, Dr. Flores,
and Dr. Jessup.

18:04.561 --> 18:06.737
My new attendings.
Building the dream team.

18:08.348 --> 18:09.827
- You're all so...

18:13.657 --> 18:15.181
- Young?

18:15.224 --> 18:16.704
- I--Uh, no, I was--
I was going to say--

18:16.747 --> 18:18.314
- Excellent surgeons?

18:18.358 --> 18:20.360
Because they all come with
glowing recommendations.

18:20.403 --> 18:22.666
- Yes, I'm sure.
Is Dr. Merritt around?

18:22.710 --> 18:24.494
He's the one who
saved Arthur's life.

18:24.538 --> 18:27.715
- Uh, Dr. Merritt is actually
no longer working here.

18:27.758 --> 18:28.759
- Did he retire?

18:28.803 --> 18:31.588
- Well, he was...
let go.

18:33.024 --> 18:34.722
- By whom?

18:34.765 --> 18:35.897
- Uh, me.

18:35.940 --> 18:37.377
- Max.

18:37.420 --> 18:38.813
You're not
answering your pager.

18:38.856 --> 18:39.814
- Dr. Bloom, this is--
- We need to talk.

18:39.857 --> 18:40.858
- Okay.
Excuse me.

18:40.902 --> 18:42.382
- Right this way, miss.

18:42.425 --> 18:43.774
- I am with the--
- I know, the money lady.

18:43.818 --> 18:45.298
- Yeah.
- I'm sorry.

18:45.341 --> 18:46.951
We've got a pregnant woman
up in corrections

18:46.995 --> 18:48.518
who's got HELLPS syndrome

18:48.562 --> 18:50.390
complicated by
maternal seizures.

18:50.433 --> 18:53.523
She needs to deliver her baby
ASAP or both are going to die.

18:53.567 --> 18:54.524
- How many weeks?

18:54.568 --> 18:55.569
- 32.

18:55.612 --> 18:56.787
- Okay, so do it.
Deliver.

18:56.831 --> 18:58.049
- She won't let us.

18:58.093 --> 19:00.835
[dramatic music]

19:00.878 --> 19:02.445
♪

19:02.489 --> 19:04.317
- Excuse me.
I have to deal with something.

19:04.360 --> 19:08.321
♪

19:08.364 --> 19:10.366
- You got anything
in your pockets,

19:10.410 --> 19:13.413
put it on the belt.

19:13.456 --> 19:15.632
Now, this might still
be the hospital.

19:15.676 --> 19:17.591
But these are real prisoners.

19:17.634 --> 19:20.463
So keep your distance
for your own protection.

19:20.507 --> 19:22.639
- Yeah.
Yeah, I keep hearing that.

19:22.683 --> 19:25.468
[gate buzzing]

19:33.302 --> 19:34.738
[gate buzzing]

19:34.782 --> 19:37.741
[indistinct radio chatter]

19:37.785 --> 19:43.530
♪

19:43.573 --> 19:45.009
Janelle.

19:45.053 --> 19:46.794
I've got someone here
who wants to talk to you.

19:46.837 --> 19:48.578
- I don't need a shrink.

19:48.622 --> 19:50.972
- That's good,
'cause I'm not a shrink.

19:51.015 --> 19:52.974
Just the medical director.

19:53.017 --> 19:54.497
Max.

19:56.151 --> 19:58.414
Dr. Bloom tells me you're
refusing treatment.

20:01.330 --> 20:04.464
Janelle, your red blood cells
are breaking down.

20:04.507 --> 20:08.076
And your liver is barely
functioning.

20:08.119 --> 20:10.905
If you don't deliver
this baby now,

20:10.948 --> 20:12.994
you are both going to die.

20:13.037 --> 20:15.301
- I won't have her in prison.

20:15.344 --> 20:16.519
I know what'll happen.

20:16.563 --> 20:18.478
The same thing that
happened to me.

20:19.870 --> 20:21.481
- Foster care.

20:21.524 --> 20:25.441
- Do you have anyone who
could take care of her

20:25.485 --> 20:26.486
until you're released?

20:26.529 --> 20:29.445
Do you have any family?

20:29.489 --> 20:31.012
- No.

20:32.753 --> 20:34.929
I get out in six weeks.

20:34.972 --> 20:37.845
Can't you just do something
to keep her inside of me

20:37.888 --> 20:39.063
for just six weeks, please?

20:39.107 --> 20:40.369
- You won't make it.

20:42.153 --> 20:44.504
- I gotta try.
For her.

20:44.547 --> 20:46.680
I'm gonna try.

20:46.723 --> 20:48.856
- Janelle, if you don't give
consent to deliver this baby,

20:48.899 --> 20:50.640
the court is gonna
make you deliver.

20:50.684 --> 20:52.686
And I don't wanna
put you through that.

20:52.729 --> 20:54.818
- So she loses either way?

20:57.952 --> 21:00.041
- No.

21:00.084 --> 21:03.479
I won't let that happen.

21:03.523 --> 21:05.699
- What does that mean?

21:05.742 --> 21:08.832
- It means...

21:08.876 --> 21:11.574
I will find a way...

21:11.618 --> 21:14.708
to take care of you both.

21:21.845 --> 21:25.545
Okay?

21:25.588 --> 21:28.417
There's always a way.

21:28.461 --> 21:31.420
[dramatic music]

21:31.464 --> 21:35.032
♪

21:35.076 --> 21:36.991
- I'll, uh, call the OB.

21:37.034 --> 21:38.688
- We need blood.
Two units type and cross.

21:38.732 --> 21:42.083
And FFP in case her
platelets bottom out.

21:42.126 --> 21:44.825
♪

21:44.868 --> 21:46.217
- I just don't know how
much more description

21:46.261 --> 21:47.871
you could possibly need.

21:47.915 --> 21:49.525
Three people have seen
the guy running naked

21:49.569 --> 21:50.526
through the halls.

21:50.570 --> 21:51.745
He's--
[laughs]

21:51.788 --> 21:53.573
He's a naked man,
for God's sake.

21:53.616 --> 21:56.880
He's--He's naked and he's
probably very distraught.

21:56.924 --> 21:58.752
He just lost his fiancée, so--
- Dr. Frome?

21:58.795 --> 22:00.841
- Yeah, what?
- I'm Maddy Gianni.

22:00.884 --> 22:02.451
Ray DeMarco's fiancée.

22:07.978 --> 22:08.196
.

22:08.239 --> 22:10.546
- Make yourself
comfortable, okay?

22:10.590 --> 22:11.547
Just sit tight.
It's okay.

22:11.591 --> 22:14.158
[percussive music]

22:14.202 --> 22:16.335
- She looks quite healthy
for a dead person.

22:16.378 --> 22:18.249
- I mean, she's pretty upset,
but yeah.

22:18.293 --> 22:19.555
She's definitely alive.

22:19.599 --> 22:21.470
- So, why was Mr. DeMarco
in that cemetery?

22:21.514 --> 22:23.254
- I have no idea.

22:23.298 --> 22:25.648
She said a week ago everything
was fine, you know?

22:25.692 --> 22:27.476
The love of her life,
and then boom.

22:27.520 --> 22:29.260
He just drops out,
stops taking her calls,

22:29.304 --> 22:30.392
stops going to work--

22:30.436 --> 22:32.220
- Disappears?
- Oh, my God.

22:32.263 --> 22:33.395
- So, when did
she last see him?

22:33.439 --> 22:35.484
- You asking me genuinely?

22:35.528 --> 22:37.530
Two days ago.

22:37.573 --> 22:39.401
The only reason she even knew
he was here was 'cause the cops

22:39.445 --> 22:41.229
found his wallet
and they called her.

22:41.272 --> 22:42.491
- Did you happen to mention
that the love of her life

22:42.535 --> 22:44.232
has gone missing?

22:44.275 --> 22:47.104
- Uh, I was kinda hoping
that you might cover that.

22:53.197 --> 22:55.330
- [sighs]

22:57.071 --> 23:00.422
- Okay, Mr. DeMarco's
tox labs are in.

23:00.466 --> 23:02.642
Didn't the woman say
anything about drug use?

23:02.685 --> 23:04.034
- Mmm, she swears he was clean,

23:04.078 --> 23:05.253
but Ray definitely
had track marks.

23:05.296 --> 23:06.428
He injected something.

23:06.472 --> 23:07.734
- Indeed.

23:07.777 --> 23:09.431
Trace amounts
of glutaraldehyde.

23:09.475 --> 23:11.607
- Mmm.
Glutaraldehyde.

23:11.651 --> 23:13.435
I don't know what that is.

23:13.479 --> 23:16.307
- Did the man actually say
that his fiancée was dead?

23:16.351 --> 23:19.006
- Well, I don't know if he
used that word exactly,

23:19.049 --> 23:20.703
but he was going on
about her in past tense,

23:20.747 --> 23:23.053
how he lost her,
and he was digging up a grave,

23:23.097 --> 23:24.403
let's not forget.

23:24.446 --> 23:25.404
- The common name
for glutaraldehyde

23:25.447 --> 23:29.277
is embalming fluid.

23:29.320 --> 23:32.454
- Oh, holy hell.

23:32.498 --> 23:34.151
He wasn't digging up her grave.

23:34.195 --> 23:36.066
He was digging his own.

23:36.110 --> 23:38.155
- Yeah, because he doesn't
think his fiancée is dead but--

23:38.199 --> 23:41.637
- He thinks he is.

23:41.681 --> 23:43.160
I think I know where he is.

23:43.204 --> 23:47.164
[percussive music]

23:48.557 --> 23:52.648
Okay, out you get.
[groans]

23:52.692 --> 23:57.392
♪

23:57.436 --> 23:59.350
You're killing me, Ray.

23:59.394 --> 24:01.091
- Yeah, Dr. Max Goodwin.

24:01.135 --> 24:02.571
I'm the Medical Director
at New Amsterdam Hospital.

24:02.615 --> 24:03.572
You're dressed.

24:03.616 --> 24:04.573
- I'm leaving.

24:04.617 --> 24:05.574
- Now?

24:05.618 --> 24:07.358
- Later.

24:07.402 --> 24:09.752
- I need to talk
to the Mayor about a patient

24:09.796 --> 24:11.711
in the corrections ward.

24:11.754 --> 24:13.190
Yes, a prisoner.

24:13.234 --> 24:14.670
Were you even
gonna say goodbye?

24:14.714 --> 24:16.629
- Of course.

24:16.672 --> 24:19.240
And my folks said you can come
up every weekend if you want.

24:19.283 --> 24:21.503
- I don't.
I don't want.

24:21.547 --> 24:24.201
Yes, the Mayor
can call me back.

24:24.245 --> 24:27.291
Just please tell him
it has to be very soon.

24:27.335 --> 24:28.510
Thank you.

24:28.554 --> 24:30.207
[phone beeps]

24:30.251 --> 24:32.209
- You're talking to the Mayor?

24:32.253 --> 24:33.646
- I'm very powerful.

24:36.736 --> 24:38.781
Please don't go.

24:38.825 --> 24:41.131
- I would need a bigger room.

24:41.175 --> 24:43.177
- We have the
President's suite.

24:43.220 --> 24:45.135
For the, you know, President.

24:45.179 --> 24:49.400
- Max, you belong here,
not me.

24:49.444 --> 24:50.663
- I belong with you.

24:52.447 --> 24:53.492
- We tried that.

24:53.535 --> 24:54.710
- And I messed it up,
I know.

24:54.754 --> 24:57.539
But I broke
a lot of promises.

24:57.583 --> 25:01.717
And I'm just trying
not to break any more.

25:01.761 --> 25:04.633
- I know.

25:04.677 --> 25:07.767
And I do love you.

25:07.810 --> 25:10.465
To my core.

25:10.509 --> 25:15.470
But this is what has to happen,
and I'm okay with it now.

25:16.558 --> 25:18.299
And Luna will be, too.

25:18.342 --> 25:19.648
And when you come
to Connecticut,

25:19.692 --> 25:21.432
we'll all be together.

25:22.825 --> 25:24.261
- I hate Connecticut.

25:24.305 --> 25:25.262
[cell phone vibrates]

25:25.306 --> 25:27.743
Yeah.
Right, yes.

25:27.787 --> 25:31.312
- Go. Go.
- I--Mr. Mayor, um,

25:31.355 --> 25:33.880
Sorry to bother you,
but this is important.

25:33.923 --> 25:35.882
if you just have--

25:35.925 --> 25:38.275
[elevator dings]

25:38.319 --> 25:41.540
- Hey.
- Hi.

25:41.583 --> 25:44.717
Nice bag.
- You want it?

25:44.760 --> 25:46.588
- Rough day?

25:46.632 --> 25:48.634
- Just the ongoing
discovery that the world

25:48.677 --> 25:50.461
thinks I'm a fraud.

25:50.505 --> 25:52.551
- Well, I kinda doubt that.

25:52.594 --> 25:55.205
- Seems my outside commitments
have relieved me

25:55.249 --> 25:56.598
of all credibility.

25:56.642 --> 25:58.818
This was a gift, by the way.

25:58.861 --> 26:02.386
- Hey, look, I get that you're
upset, but you're amazing.

26:02.430 --> 26:04.563
You're an excellent physician
and you raised a ton of money

26:04.606 --> 26:05.651
for this place.

26:05.694 --> 26:07.304
- Patients don't
care about that.

26:07.348 --> 26:08.741
Nor should they.

26:08.784 --> 26:10.481
They just want a doctor
they can trust,

26:10.525 --> 26:12.614
and right now Doctor Helen
isn't worth trusting.

26:12.658 --> 26:14.181
- Then tell them
why they should.

26:14.224 --> 26:15.225
[elevator door dings]

26:15.269 --> 26:16.618
[dramatic music]

26:16.662 --> 26:19.621
Oh, hey, uh,
can I really have that bag?

26:19.665 --> 26:21.754
- Piss off.

26:23.582 --> 26:25.496
- Embalming fluid?

26:25.540 --> 26:27.368
- Yeah, we believe that Ray
is suffering from something

26:27.411 --> 26:28.935
called Cotard's Syndrome.

26:28.978 --> 26:31.285
It's a rare disease where
the victim actually believes

26:31.328 --> 26:32.634
that they've passed on.

26:32.678 --> 26:35.202
Sometimes as a result,
they can imagine

26:35.245 --> 26:37.508
that they can't be seen.

26:37.552 --> 26:39.162
Like a ghost.

26:39.206 --> 26:41.251
- Ray thinks he's dead?

26:42.513 --> 26:45.647
But he's talking.
Dead people don't talk.

26:45.691 --> 26:47.910
- It's not logical.

26:47.954 --> 26:49.346
It's delusional.

26:49.390 --> 26:51.566
- Why can't he feel his arms?

26:51.610 --> 26:54.308
- Well, we don't know yet,
but Dr. Kapoor is giving him

26:54.351 --> 26:56.789
an MRI as we speak,
so he's in good hands.

26:56.832 --> 26:59.226
- [crying]

26:59.269 --> 27:01.620
- Hey.

27:01.663 --> 27:02.664
You know...

27:04.231 --> 27:08.801
You know, the, uh--the
good news is, um,

27:08.844 --> 27:11.542
that lack of feeling
could be neurological.

27:11.586 --> 27:13.370
Um, Cotard's
wouldn't cause that,

27:13.414 --> 27:15.634
and neither would
embalming fluid.

27:15.677 --> 27:19.638
- I think you and I have a very
different idea of good news.

27:21.944 --> 27:24.643
[crying]

27:33.739 --> 27:36.698
- Okay, what do we got?

27:36.742 --> 27:38.569
Tumor?

27:38.613 --> 27:41.268
- Pressure from which
is causing him delusions.

27:41.311 --> 27:43.574
Out of body feeling.

27:43.618 --> 27:45.402
Numbness.

27:45.446 --> 27:48.492
So, while Mr. DeMarco
is certainly not dead,

27:48.536 --> 27:49.929
he may well be soon.

27:49.972 --> 27:52.758
[elevator door dings]

27:58.720 --> 27:59.939
- Doctor.
- Doctor.

27:59.982 --> 28:01.331
- Where are you racing to?

28:01.375 --> 28:02.419
- Correctional ward.

28:02.463 --> 28:03.464
I've got a baby on the way.

28:03.507 --> 28:05.466
- Nice.
- Hopefully.

28:05.509 --> 28:07.033
I see you're putting
together quite the team.

28:07.076 --> 28:08.338
- Uh-huh.

28:08.382 --> 28:09.513
- Any future wives in the mix?

28:09.557 --> 28:11.341
- Oh, man.

28:11.385 --> 28:12.734
- What?

28:12.778 --> 28:14.954
- All these women have
better resumes than we do.

28:14.997 --> 28:16.651
- I'd expect nothing less.

28:16.695 --> 28:18.348
I just, uh--I couldn't
help but notice--

28:18.392 --> 28:19.828
- Right, right.

28:19.872 --> 28:23.397
Everybody notices something,
but nobody says anything.

28:23.440 --> 28:25.573
So please, just--just say it.

28:25.616 --> 28:28.315
- I was gonna say how
attractive they all are.

28:30.317 --> 28:32.667
- Didn't stop you
from getting hired.

28:32.711 --> 28:34.451
- Don't make this about me.

28:34.495 --> 28:35.975
- No, but it is.

28:36.018 --> 28:37.977
Look, you ought to know more
than anyone how often

28:38.020 --> 28:39.500
women are overlooked
for surgical positions.

28:39.543 --> 28:40.936
- A lot.

28:40.980 --> 28:43.547
- Only 19% of the surgeons
in this country are women.

28:43.591 --> 28:45.419
- I mean, I didn't know
the exact statistic.

28:45.462 --> 28:48.030
- You wanna hear the stats
for women of color?

28:48.074 --> 28:49.771
- I'm scared to ask.

28:49.815 --> 28:52.426
- They don't exist.

28:52.469 --> 28:55.516
So, while I intend to hire
folks of every ethnicity

28:55.559 --> 28:57.474
and gender for my staff,

28:57.518 --> 28:59.912
I'm hiring women
of color first.

28:59.955 --> 29:02.784
[elevator door dings]

29:04.960 --> 29:06.657
I believe this is you.

29:06.701 --> 29:09.660
[percussive music]

29:09.704 --> 29:12.794
♪

29:12.838 --> 29:14.665
- Mr. Mayor, I understand.

29:14.709 --> 29:17.103
I was just hoping that
in this particular case,

29:17.146 --> 29:19.496
you might make an exception
for a pregnant young woman

29:19.540 --> 29:21.977
six weeks from being--

29:22.021 --> 29:23.065
[phone ringing]

29:23.109 --> 29:25.067
Thank you for calling back.

29:25.111 --> 29:27.678
Okay.

29:27.722 --> 29:29.680
Mrs. Ryland.
- Hello, Max.

29:29.724 --> 29:30.812
- I'm surprised
you're still here.

29:30.856 --> 29:32.640
- I told you I cleared the day.

29:32.683 --> 29:34.033
- Yeah, but--

29:34.076 --> 29:36.383
- The Dean sent a copy
of some plans he had drawn.

29:36.426 --> 29:37.950
Would you like to see them?

29:37.993 --> 29:40.039
- Why not?

29:42.737 --> 29:44.130
Oh, wow.

29:44.173 --> 29:45.784
[chuckles]

29:45.827 --> 29:48.961
Arthur Ryland Heart Institute.

29:50.527 --> 29:52.007
At University Hospital.

29:52.051 --> 29:53.530
- State of the art facility.

29:53.574 --> 29:55.794
Arthur's name
in big gold letters.

29:58.013 --> 29:59.362
Tell me something, Max.

29:59.406 --> 30:01.147
Why did you fire Dr. Merritt?

30:03.584 --> 30:05.934
- 'Cause he only
cared about money.

30:07.893 --> 30:09.895
- Just like my husband.

30:11.897 --> 30:15.074
I think the gold letters
are garish and vulgar.

30:16.902 --> 30:18.991
But it's exactly what
Arthur would have wanted.

30:21.994 --> 30:26.128
- Mrs. Ryland,
what do you want?

30:30.045 --> 30:33.396
- Fresh bag normal saline
running open wide.

30:33.440 --> 30:34.745
- Crowning now.
- I can't feel anything.

30:34.789 --> 30:36.443
- Okay, gotta get
through to the neck.

30:36.486 --> 30:39.750
- Okay, that's the epidural.
Just--Just hold my hand.

30:39.794 --> 30:40.969
- Excellent.

30:41.013 --> 30:43.493
- Clear.
- Easy now.

30:43.537 --> 30:45.104
Shoulders in position.
- Right, right.

30:45.147 --> 30:46.845
Just a little twist.

30:46.888 --> 30:51.458
And we have a newborn baby.

30:51.501 --> 30:53.503
Baby girl.
- [crying]

30:53.547 --> 30:54.896
- Moving all four extremities.

30:54.940 --> 30:58.769
- [crying]

30:58.813 --> 31:00.075
- She looks really good.

31:00.119 --> 31:01.598
They're just gonna
take her over there.

31:01.642 --> 31:03.774
Gonna wash her up.
How are you feeling?

31:03.818 --> 31:05.080
Are you okay?
- Mm-hmm.

31:05.124 --> 31:07.778
- You okay?
- I'm tired.

31:07.822 --> 31:12.783
- [crying]

31:18.964 --> 31:20.574
- Look how beautiful she is.

31:20.617 --> 31:25.666
- [crying]

31:25.709 --> 31:28.756
- Wait, wait, wait, wait, wait.

31:28.799 --> 31:33.021
Your friend said that he would
find a way for us to be, um,

31:33.065 --> 31:35.023
together and to take
care of us.

31:35.067 --> 31:36.720
- He's working on it.

31:36.764 --> 31:39.114
- No, no, no,
but my baby's already here.

31:39.158 --> 31:40.768
She's already here.

31:40.811 --> 31:43.814
I just can't--

31:43.858 --> 31:47.644
- Just--Just--Just hold her.
No one's taking her right now.

31:47.688 --> 31:50.125
- No, she's already here.
Where is he?

31:50.169 --> 31:51.648
- Janelle, no, no one's--

31:51.692 --> 31:53.259
no one's gonna
take her right now.

31:53.302 --> 31:56.131
- No, no, no, but I can't.
I can't.

31:56.175 --> 31:57.741
- I can't take her.
- Janelle, listen to me.

31:57.785 --> 32:00.092
- No, I have to give her up.
I can't.

32:00.135 --> 32:02.050
I can't.
I won't.

32:02.094 --> 32:05.140
- [crying]

32:14.802 --> 32:15.150
.

32:15.194 --> 32:18.458
[phones ringing]

32:18.501 --> 32:21.548
- We never had children,
Arthur and I.

32:21.591 --> 32:25.160
I wanted them, of course.
He said he did, too.

32:26.640 --> 32:29.251
But after we got married,
he changed his mind.

32:29.295 --> 32:32.254
[dramatic music]

32:32.298 --> 32:37.564
♪

32:37.607 --> 32:39.870
I shouldn't have
let that happen.

32:39.914 --> 32:41.568
What is this?

32:41.611 --> 32:42.830
♪

32:42.873 --> 32:44.353
- We call it Kangaroo Care.

32:44.397 --> 32:46.138
Instead of traditional
incubators,

32:46.181 --> 32:48.575
these volunteers provide
low birth weight premies

32:48.618 --> 32:51.230
with human contact.

32:51.273 --> 32:53.406
Skin-to-skin.

32:53.449 --> 32:58.846
And, um, I think that one
right there was just born.

32:58.889 --> 33:01.631
♪

33:01.675 --> 33:03.372
- She's so small.

33:03.416 --> 33:07.159
- Yeah.

33:07.202 --> 33:10.379
- Will she be all right?

33:13.469 --> 33:16.429
- Mrs. Ryland, what if--
what if instead

33:16.472 --> 33:19.780
of giving your husband's money
to University or New Amsterdam,

33:19.823 --> 33:22.783
you gave it to someplace
else altogether?

33:22.826 --> 33:26.265
There wouldn't be a fancy
building with your husband's

33:26.308 --> 33:28.571
name on it,
but your contribution could

33:28.615 --> 33:30.312
potentially change
the course of hundreds--

33:30.356 --> 33:33.663
if not thousands--of lives.

33:40.235 --> 33:43.804
- Rikers Island.

33:43.847 --> 33:47.329
You wanna give $10 million
to Rikers Island?

33:49.940 --> 33:52.813
- The Ryland Endowment would be
used to convert unused space

33:52.856 --> 33:56.382
to a nursery
and Kangaroo Care unit.

33:56.425 --> 33:58.601
This would allow incarcerated
mothers to keep their newborns

33:58.645 --> 34:00.342
close while they complete
their sentence.

34:00.386 --> 34:03.302
And even though the unit itself
won't be ready for weeks,

34:03.345 --> 34:07.567
they can designate a room
and start the program today.

34:07.610 --> 34:08.655
With Janelle Mason.

34:08.698 --> 34:10.135
- Max--

34:10.178 --> 34:11.571
- I've already spoken
to the Warden,

34:11.614 --> 34:13.268
and there is no law
against doing this.

34:13.312 --> 34:16.445
The only thing required is--
- Is money.

34:16.489 --> 34:21.146
- And like us,
Rikers needs money.

34:21.189 --> 34:24.888
- Do you really believe
that Arthur would want this?

34:24.932 --> 34:30.851
- No.
But I do.

34:30.894 --> 34:33.506
- Isn't our job
to provide our patients

34:33.549 --> 34:34.855
with the best possible care?

34:34.898 --> 34:36.683
- I know very well
what our job is.

34:36.726 --> 34:38.859
- But isn't it also to help
people out in the world

34:38.902 --> 34:42.384
not become patients?

34:42.428 --> 34:46.693
Even if the system is broken,
we can offer them a path.

34:46.736 --> 34:48.564
Because if we don't,
we are just gonna see

34:48.608 --> 34:51.437
each generation back
here again and again.

34:51.480 --> 34:54.744
Babies returning with obesity
before the age of six.

34:54.788 --> 34:57.356
Foster kids coming back
as psych patients

34:57.399 --> 34:58.748
before they can even vote.

34:58.792 --> 35:01.577
So we need to break the chain.

35:01.621 --> 35:04.928
But we can only help people
if we ourselves are willing

35:04.972 --> 35:08.236
to take risks.

35:08.280 --> 35:13.676
'Cause change
is always possible.

35:15.678 --> 35:16.940
- I'm sorry, Peter.

35:16.984 --> 35:19.334
I know you wanted
a different outcome.

35:19.378 --> 35:22.207
And Max tried to honor that.

35:22.250 --> 35:23.947
But this was all me.

35:29.953 --> 35:33.392
- Well, thank you
for your contribution.

35:33.435 --> 35:36.395
[Jose Gonzalez's "Heartbeats"]

35:36.438 --> 35:43.445
♪

35:45.926 --> 35:47.928
- Janelle?

35:47.971 --> 35:52.846
When you go back,
your baby's going with you.

35:52.889 --> 35:59.940
♪

36:03.117 --> 36:05.772
- ♪ One night to be confused

36:05.815 --> 36:08.688
♪ One night
to speed up truth ♪

36:08.731 --> 36:11.299
♪ We had a promise made

36:11.343 --> 36:13.954
♪ Four hands and then away

36:13.997 --> 36:16.435
♪ Both under influence

36:16.478 --> 36:18.611
- We're, uh, starting Ray
on steroids in order to relieve

36:18.654 --> 36:20.395
the pressure from the tumor,
and by tomorrow

36:20.439 --> 36:21.831
his delusion should be gone.

36:21.875 --> 36:24.660
- And the tumor itself?

36:24.704 --> 36:26.358
- Treatable.

36:26.401 --> 36:30.318
- ♪ To call for hands
of above ♪

36:30.362 --> 36:31.972
♪ To lean on

36:32.015 --> 36:35.584
♪ Wouldn't be good enough

36:35.628 --> 36:38.370
♪ For me no

36:38.413 --> 36:40.981
- What did they say?

36:41.024 --> 36:45.768
- That tomorrow they're gonna
bring you back to life.

36:45.812 --> 36:48.510
- ♪ The start a simple touch

36:48.554 --> 36:51.774
♪ One night to push
and scream ♪

36:51.818 --> 36:54.081
♪ And then relief

36:54.124 --> 36:56.692
♪ Ten days of perfect tunes

36:56.736 --> 36:58.955
♪ The colors red and blue

36:58.999 --> 37:00.653
- [clears throat]

37:00.696 --> 37:01.654
- ♪ We had a promise made

37:01.697 --> 37:02.785
- Excuse me.

37:02.829 --> 37:05.440
- ♪ We were in love

37:05.484 --> 37:08.965
- What does ghosted mean?

37:09.009 --> 37:13.405
- Oh, that's when someone,
uh, that you love, uh,

37:13.448 --> 37:16.843
disappears from your life.

37:16.886 --> 37:18.497
Who ghosted you?

37:18.540 --> 37:20.629
- ♪ To call for hands
of above ♪

37:20.673 --> 37:21.630
- My son.

37:21.674 --> 37:24.851
- ♪ To lean on

37:24.894 --> 37:28.115
- But I think
I ghosted him first.

37:28.158 --> 37:34.991
- ♪ And you, you knew
the hand of the devil ♪

37:35.035 --> 37:38.821
♪

37:38.865 --> 37:42.172
♪ And you

37:42.216 --> 37:45.480
♪ To call for hands of above

37:45.524 --> 37:47.482
♪ To lean on

37:47.526 --> 37:50.877
♪ Wouldn't be good enough

37:50.920 --> 37:52.792
♪ For me no

37:52.835 --> 37:55.969
♪ To call for hands of above

37:56.012 --> 37:58.058
♪ To lean on

37:58.101 --> 38:02.541
♪ Wouldn't be good enough

38:02.584 --> 38:04.891
♪

38:07.154 --> 38:09.548
[door closes]

38:09.591 --> 38:11.071
- [sighs]
Dr. Sharpe, I need you to--

38:11.114 --> 38:12.551
- Do you have any idea
how long people wait

38:12.594 --> 38:14.117
to get an appointment with me?

38:14.161 --> 38:15.684
- Sorry, what?

38:15.728 --> 38:17.773
- I'm an excellent physician.
- Yeah.

38:17.817 --> 38:20.907
- An extraordinary physician.

38:20.950 --> 38:22.822
And I have a radiant smile.

38:22.865 --> 38:24.911
- Okay, can you let me finish?

38:24.954 --> 38:26.695
- No, do--Can
you let me finish?

38:26.739 --> 38:28.175
If you don't have faith
in my abilities,

38:28.218 --> 38:30.133
if you can't say,
"I need you to be my doctor,"

38:30.177 --> 38:31.918
then you're making a mistake
that could cost you your life.

38:31.961 --> 38:36.662
- I need you to be my doctor.

38:39.969 --> 38:43.408
I wanna be a father.

38:43.451 --> 38:46.759
And I wanna be a husband.

38:46.802 --> 38:51.503
So I'm putting my life...

38:51.546 --> 38:54.070
In your hands.

38:59.641 --> 39:01.208
- I won't bargain with you,
Max.

39:01.251 --> 39:02.862
- I know.
- I won't negotiate.

39:02.905 --> 39:05.430
- I'm all in.

39:05.473 --> 39:06.692
Whatever you say,
I'll do it.

39:06.735 --> 39:09.999
Just please be my doctor.

39:14.700 --> 39:20.140
How much time do
I have before the, uh,

39:20.183 --> 39:21.184
chemo and radiation?

39:21.228 --> 39:24.753
- Three weeks.

39:24.797 --> 39:25.972
- Is there any way
that we could kind of--

39:26.015 --> 39:27.190
- Max.
- Just kidding.

39:27.234 --> 39:28.844
- [sighs]

39:28.888 --> 39:32.282
- Three weeks.

39:32.326 --> 39:35.808
Okay.

39:35.851 --> 39:40.769
If you'll excuse me,
I don't have a lot of time.

39:48.777 --> 39:51.258
- Where's Georgia?
- Discharged.

39:51.301 --> 39:54.261
[dramatic music]

39:54.304 --> 40:01.268
♪

40:07.970 --> 40:15.021
♪

40:24.726 --> 40:26.206
- Hey, wait, wait, wait, wait,
wait, wait, wait, wait.

40:26.249 --> 40:27.860
Wait.

40:27.903 --> 40:29.209
I'm not letting you do this,
okay?

40:29.252 --> 40:31.516
You're not going
to Connecticut.

40:31.559 --> 40:33.518
- We're not there yet.

40:33.561 --> 40:35.824
- I know, but she is, Georgia.
She's there.

40:35.868 --> 40:37.043
Here.

40:37.086 --> 40:39.567
Our--Our daughter
is almost here.

40:39.611 --> 40:41.700
And the first thing that
she's gonna see in this world

40:41.743 --> 40:44.180
is your beautiful face.

40:44.224 --> 40:46.835
She's gonna love you
like I love you.

40:46.879 --> 40:50.970
And then maybe after a really,
really long look,

40:51.013 --> 40:53.712
she is gonna turn
and look for me.

40:53.755 --> 40:58.673
If I'm not there,
she is gonna wonder where I am.

40:58.717 --> 41:00.893
Where did I go?

41:00.936 --> 41:03.243
She knows my voice.

41:03.286 --> 41:07.639
Georgia, she knows my voice.

41:07.682 --> 41:12.078
I have to be there.

41:12.121 --> 41:16.735
I have to be here.

41:16.778 --> 41:20.608
Let me--Let me take you home.

41:20.652 --> 41:22.828
Let me take care of you both,
please.

41:22.871 --> 41:24.394
In our house.
Let me help you.

41:24.438 --> 41:27.702
Because if I can't help my
wife and my daughter, then...

41:27.746 --> 41:33.621
♪

41:33.665 --> 41:36.972
And I--If it's
really not working,

41:37.016 --> 41:39.801
say the word and I promise
I will drive you

41:39.845 --> 41:42.717
to Connecticut myself.

41:42.761 --> 41:49.811
♪

41:55.469 --> 41:56.949
- Okay.
- Great.

41:56.992 --> 41:59.691
Okay.
Okay.

41:59.734 --> 42:06.698
♪

42:06.741 --> 42:11.180
I'm gonna be a father.
I'm gonna be a father!

42:11.224 --> 42:12.181
That's my wife.

42:12.225 --> 42:14.140
It's all right.

42:14.183 --> 42:17.665
I'm gonna be a father!
